The variables were recategorized as follows to better suit a logistical regression model:
dat <- dat.voting %>%
  filter(VCF0004 == 2012 | VCF0004 == 2016) %>%
  rename(candidate = VCF0704a, 
         year = VCF0004, 
         race = VCF0105a, 
         age = VCF0101, 
         gender = VCF0104, 
         income = VCF0114, 
         religion = VCF0128, 
         education = VCF0140a, 
         marital = VCF0147, 
         class = VCF0148a, 
         party = VCF0302, 
         hispanic = VCF0108, 
         south = VCF0113) %>%
  filter(age != 0, race != 9, candidate != 0, gender != 0, gender != 3, income != 0, religion != 0, education != 8, education != 9, class != 0, marital != 9, party != 0, class !=9, hispanic != 8, hispanic != 9, south != 0) %>%
  mutate(candidate = as.factor(case_when(
    candidate == "1" ~ "democrat",
    candidate == "2" ~ "republican",
    TRUE ~ as.character(candidate)
  ))) %>%
  mutate(race = as.factor(case_when(
    race == 1 ~ "white",
    race == 2 ~ "black",
    TRUE ~ "other"
  ))) %>%
  mutate(age = as.factor(case_when(
    age >= 17 & age < 35 ~ "youth",
    age >= 35 & age < 65 ~ "middle age",
    age >= 65 ~ "retirees"
  ))) %>%
  mutate(gender = as.factor(case_when(
    gender == 1 ~ "male",
    gender == 2 ~ "female",
    TRUE ~ "other"
  ))) %>%
  mutate(income = as.factor(case_when(
    income %in% c(1, 2) ~ "low",
    income == 3 ~ "middle",
    income %in% c(4, 5) ~ "high",
    TRUE ~ "other"
  ))) %>%
  mutate(religion = as.factor(case_when(
    religion == 1 ~ "protestant",
    religion == 2 ~ "catholic",
    TRUE ~ "other"
  ))) %>%
  mutate(education = as.factor(case_when(
    education %in% c(1, 2) ~ "no hs",
    education %in% c(3, 4) ~ "hs",
    education %in% c(5, 6, 7) ~ "college",
    TRUE ~ "other"
  ))) %>%
  mutate(marital = as.factor(case_when(
    marital == 1 ~ "married",
    TRUE ~ "unmarried"
  ))) %>%
  mutate(class = as.factor(case_when(
    class %in% c(1, 2, 3) ~ "working",
    class %in% c(4, 5, 6) ~ "middle",
    TRUE ~ "other"
  ))) %>%
  mutate(party = as.factor(case_when(
    party == 1 ~ "republican",
    party == 5 ~ "democrat",
    TRUE ~ "other"
  ))) %>%
  mutate(hispanic = as.factor(case_when(
    hispanic == 1 ~ "hispanic",
    TRUE ~ "non-hispanic"
  ))) %>%
  mutate(south = as.factor(case_when(
    south == 1 ~ "south",
    TRUE ~ "non-south"
  )))

Race categories were reduced to white, black and other
Age was recategorised from continuous to categorical data. This was done as age categories based on voter’s stages in life may more accurately represent voting behavior. Age 18-35 were categorised as young voters, age 35-65 as middle age voters and age 65+ as retirees.
Gender was categorised as male and female. “other” gender category was removed since it existed only in the 2016 data and not in 2012.
Income was recategorised into low, middle and high in 3 equal quatiles
Religion was recategorised to protestant, catholic and other for a better distribution of categories. Jews were included in the other category as there were very few jewish voters in the data.
Education was recategorised into no high school high school and college for easier interpretation of categories in the logistic regression model.
Marital status was recategorised to married and unmarried for a better distribution of values in each category and a simpler interpretation.
Class was recategorised to working class and middle class
Party identification was recategorised to republican, democrat and other, better reflecting the two party majority in the US
Hispanic was simplified to hispanic and non hispanic
South categories were retained as south and non south.

Variable selection

Considering our knowledge of the voting trends in 2012 and 2016 and by analysing the distribution of data in this dataset, voter behvaior varied along lines of race, age, gender, educational attianment,class and being in southern states. We would like to investigate if our assumptions are verified in the logistic regression analysis of this dataset. Variables such as party identification and hispanic were also included to investigate the change in voting patterns.

What do the model outcomes say about how voting patterns changed between the two years? Do these changes meet your expectations?

Model Building:

Reference categories were selected for variables as follows:
dat_2012$education <- relevel(dat_2012$education, ref = "hs")
dat_2016$education <- relevel(dat_2016$education, ref = "hs")

dat_2012$income <- relevel(dat_2012$income, ref = "middle")
dat_2016$income <- relevel(dat_2016$income, ref = "middle")

dat_2012$race <- relevel(dat_2012$race, ref = "black")
dat_2016$race <- relevel(dat_2016$race, ref = "black")

dat_2012$religion <- relevel(dat_2012$religion, ref = "catholic")
dat_2016$religion <- relevel(dat_2016$religion, ref = "catholic")

dat_2012$hispanic <- relevel(dat_2012$hispanic, ref = "non-hispanic")
dat_2016$hispanic <- relevel(dat_2016$hispanic, ref = "non-hispanic")

For education, high school only was chosen as the reference level since no high school and college appear to show more variation between 2012 and 2016 in the plots shown before and should be analysed.

For income, middle income was chosen as the reference level since low income and high income appear to show more variation between 2012 and 2016 in the plots shown before and should be analysed.

Other reference categories were set to better interpret the results and to achieve better significance levels in the models.

In 2012, on average, for white voters, the odds of voting republican are 2899% higher compared to black voters, all else being equal. The association is statistically significant at the p value <0.001 level (z value: 11.6, p-value: < 2e-16)

For white voters, the odds of voting republican reduced between 2012 and 2016, but are still astronomically higher than black voters. This is contrary to our expectations, as we believed the republican candidate’s campaign focused heavily on issues such as immigration, trade, and law and order, which would resonate with many white voters.

In 2012, on average, for voters of other races, the odds of voting republican are 1964% higher compared to black voters, all else being equal. The association is statistically significant at the p value <0.001 level (z value: 8.5, p-value: < 2e-16)

In 2016, on average, for voters of other races, the odds of voting republican are 851% higher compared to black voters, all else being equal. The association is statistically significant at the p value <0.001 level (z value: 5.2, p-value: < 2.32e-07)

For voters of other races, the odds of voting republican also reduced significantly between 2012 and 2016 but are still higher than black voters. This is as we expected according to the 2016 republican candidate’s campaign messaging.


Age

In 2012, on average, for retired voters, the odds of voting republican are 25.9% higher compared to middle-aged voters, all else being equal. The association is statistically significant at the p value <0.1 level (z value: 1.8, p-value: 0.07)

In 2016, on average, for retired voters, the odds of voting republican are 20.1% higher compared to middle-aged voters, all else being equal. The association is not statistically significant level (z value: 1.2, p-value: 0.24) Retired voters (age 65+) are more likely to vote republican than middle aged voters, and this trend continued from 2012 to 2016 with only a small reduction in the magnitude of odds ratio. In 2012, on average, for young voters, the odds of voting republican are 31.4% lower compared to middle-aged voters, all else being equal. The association is statistically significant at the p value <0.05 level (z value: -2.5, p-value: 0.01)

In 2016, on average, for young voters, the odds of voting republican are 31.9% lower compared to middle-aged voters, all else being equal. The association is statistically significant at the p value <0.05 level (z value: -2.2, p-value: 0.026)

Young voters (age 18-35) are more likely to vote republican than middle aged voters, and this trend continued from 2012 to 2016 with only a small increase in the magnitude of odds ratio. We would have expected a higher increase in the likelihood of young voters voting republican.

Voters of other religions were less likely to vote republican in 2016 compared to 2012. This is as we expected and indicates the increase in relation between conservative views and voting republican

In 2016, on average, for voters with a college education or higher, the odds of voting republican are 47.9% lower compared to voters with only a high school degree, all else being equal. The association is statistically significant at the p value <0.001 level (z value: -4.03, p-value: 5.67e-05)

Using the code chunk above, we first loaded DVRPC’s 2012 Household Travel Survey database for Households, Persons and Trips to R. We cleaned the data for trips per person to only include trips only bike, auto, and transit trips that ended at work locations. We reassigned names to the categorical numeric variables for the same and filtered to only include the first trip made by the user. At the end we selected household id, person id, travel time (model simulated), and travel distance (model simulated) to our ‘trip_cleaned’ data set.

We followed a similar process for the person traveling data set by filtering and re-coding the variables: Household ID, Person ID, Gender, Age, Education, Mode of Transportation to Work and Driver’s License. Gender and License were re-coded to o and 1 for “male” and “female” and “Yes” and “No” respectively. Age has been categorized as “Under 18 years”, “young working” for 18-34 years, “working” for 35-64 years and “retired”. Similarly to mode categories, mode of work transit has also been “car”, “transit” and “other”. Education levels have been peoples who “did not graduate”, “High School Grad”, some form of college degree as “Grad” and all else as “other”. We filtered out all the rows where data was unusable as the person refused to answer or didn’t know. We also filtered out all the NA values.

Similarly, for the Household data set, we selected the Household ID, County, type of neighborhood, household size, total number of household workers, total number of household vehicles and household income. We filtered out the unusable data and NAs and re-coded income into three categories: low, medium and high as per 2012 income inflation data. At last, we combined the three data sets by their unique Household ID and checked for any NAs or errors.

Task 3. Develop the “leanest and meanest” multinomial logit model explaining whether a traveler drove to work, took public transit, or biked. Explain how you used theory, significance level, and model fit to select variables. Briefly discuss which variables fell out in the process of model building and why. Pay particular attention to variables that were hypothesized to correspond to mode choices but were excluded from the final model. For variables that can be modeled as either numerical or categorical, explain your rationale for using either data type. For categorical variables, explain your choice of the reference category (you may set the reference category manually).

Before we develop a multi-nomial logit model explaining whether a traveler drove to work, took public transit, or biked, several steps were undertaken. First, average speeds for each mode were calculated using the given data. Then, travel times for each alternative mode were computed one at a time based on the average speeds and distance data for that mode available in the DVRPC data. A value of 10 or 10 minutes were added to the transit time calculated using this method to account for transfer (boarding and alighting time).

#calculating average speed for each mode
ave.speed <- dat %>% group_by(mode_cat) %>%
  summarise(ave_speed = mean(Model_TravDist/(Model_TravTime/60)))

#calculating travel time for alternative modes, one mode at a time
dat.car <- dat %>% filter(mode_cat == "car")
dat.transit <- dat %>% filter(mode_cat == "transit")
dat.bike <- dat %>% filter(mode_cat == "bike")

dat.car$time.car <- dat.car$Model_TravTime
dat.car$time.transit <- 60*(dat.car$Model_TravDist/ave.speed$ave_speed[3]) + 10 #assigning transfer time
dat.car$time.bike <- 60*(dat.car$Model_TravDist/ave.speed$ave_speed[1])

dat.transit$time.transit <- dat.transit$Model_TravTime + 10
dat.transit$time.car <- 60*(dat.transit$Model_TravDist/ave.speed$ave_speed[2])
dat.transit$time.bike <- 60*(dat.transit$Model_TravDist/ave.speed$ave_speed[1])

dat.bike$time.bike <- dat.bike$Model_TravTime
dat.bike$time.car <- 60*(dat.bike$Model_TravDist/ave.speed$ave_speed[2])
dat.bike$time.transit <- 60*(dat.bike$Model_TravDist/ave.speed$ave_speed[3]) + 10 #assigning transfer time

This data is stored as three different dataframe each for car, transit and bike containing 3014, 304 and 79 observations respectively. We notice that the observations for car exceed the observations for other modes. Residents in the DVRPC region overwhelmingly traveled by car. If we were to use the data as it is, our model will predict the mode choice for car very well, however it will not do so for the other modes. This means our model cannot be generalized. Therefore, we take a random sample by setting the seed to 100. set.seed(seed = 100) ensures reproducibility by setting the seed for random number generation. This is important when randomly sampling data to ensure that the same random sample can be obtained in future runs.The sample function is used to randomly sample 500 rows from the dat.car dataset. By doing this, the dataset is reduced to a subset that is more manageable while still retaining a representative sample of car mode data. This step helps balance the representation of each mode in the dataset. This helps prevent bias that may arise if one mode is over-represented or under-represented in the data.

#sub-setting to balance mode choice
set.seed(seed = 100)
rows <- sample(1:nrow(dat.car), 500)
dat.car <- dat.car[rows,]

dat <- rbind.data.frame(dat.car, dat.transit, dat.bike)

To make our final multinomial logit model realistic, we assign a monetary cost to each mode of transportation. For driving, a cost of $0.6 per mile is used, multiplied by the travel distance. For transit, a cost of 2 dollar is added as ticket cost and a non-monetary cost of 0.5 is added as a cost of inconvenience while traveling by transit. Similarly for bike, a non-monetary cost of 3 is added as a cost of inconvenience as well as wear and tear on each ride. The data is stored in a new dataframe termed dat.logit.The mlogit.data function from the mlogit package is used to shape the data into the correct format for multinomial logit modeling. The model can now provide insights into how travelers’ decisions are influenced by both monetary and non-monetary costs associated with different transportation modes.

#calculating travel costs for alternative modes
#add $0.6/mile cost for driving
dat$cost.car <- dat$Model_TravDist * 0.6 

#multiply 0.5 for non-monetary costs, add $2 for ticket
dat$cost.transit <- dat$Model_TravDist * 0.5 + 2

#add $3 for non-monetary cost and wear and tear
dat$cost.bike <- dat$Model_TravDist + 3 

#shaping data into correct format
dat.logit <- mlogit.data(dat, shape="wide", 
                      choice="mode_cat", 
                      varying=c(18:23))

We now start to build our initial model using the cost and time variables we calculated above. These are our alternative specific variables which are not user dependent. We now add individual specific variables that are derived from DVRPC survey one at a time to our model 0.


Initial Model

We first added the income categorical variable which turned out to be significant for middle and upper middle income bike usage. The home county for riders (HH_COUNTY) came out to be highly multi-collinear with area type of household (A_TYPE). However since the latter was more significant we decided to drop the former. The lack of driver’s license was also significant for transit use. Household size and household work also showed a similar preference for mode choice, however here too, HH_size was more significant and improved our model fit. Total number of vehicles in a household was also a solid indicator of mode choice in the database and was therefore retained. Gender was a binary numeric variable which we expected to be significant. The predictions matched our hypothesis about the negative relationship between bike use and women, however the relation wasn’t deemed significant enough to be considered in the final model. Age and education were other such variables that we expected to yield interesting result. Education level had little impact on our model as most of the respondents had at least a high school level degree and over 50% had some form of college degree. Thus the model had little variability to judge mode choice behavior based on just their education level. For the age categories, we set retired people as the reference category once and people ages 35-64 next. We were able to observe the negative mode choice trends for children under 18 years and retired persons. For working age population, the riders’ odds of using transit over car are lesser than other age groups.

The log-likelihood value of -450.13 indicates how well the model fits the data, with lower values indicating better fit. Task 4. In a neatly organized table, present the output from your final model. Summarize your model results in a few paragraphs. Include plots or tables that show how the probabilities of each choice change with interventions to key variables (i.e., simulated effect of interventions).

For our final model we have used the variables cost, time, income, area type, driver’s license, number of worker’s in a household and total number of vehicles available. Based on the summary for our mod.1, the model has a McFadden’s R-square of 0.41 and log-likelihood -467.62. The smaller negative log likelihood compared to several of our other regression outputs suggests a relatively better fit to model. The Likelihood ratio test (chisq) is 663.18 with p.value = < 0.000000000000000222. The p-value is astronomically small, much smaller than a typical significance level like 0.05. This indicates very strong evidence against the null hypothesis, which in the context of the Likelihood Ratio Test, means that the more complex model (the one being tested against the null) fits significantly better than the simpler model. The AIC for our final model is greater than our initial model. However AIC does not penalize for number of variables, therefore having more variables that minutely improve the model are taken into consideration. We were unable to use BIC on our model, as even though the model does not have NAs, the model is too complex for BIC. Therefore, we decided to go ahead with our final model based on it making theoretical sense and high model fit.

For the interpretation we have first calculated the percentages using coefficient for each variable. In this model we are dealing with both continuous and categorical variables.

For Alternative Specific variables:

Cost: As one mode’s cost become 1 dollar more expensive than the other modes, the odds of choosing the mode becomes 62.4% lower relative to the other modes, all else being equal. This association is statistically significant at p< 0.05 (p= 0.0000000001773344).

Time: As one mode’s travel time becomes 1 minute longer than the other modes, the odds of using the mode becomes 0.96% more relative to the other modes, all else being equal. It suggests that a slight gain in travel time does not impact people’s mode choice significantly.

For Individual Specific Variables:

  1. Income’s impact on mode choice:

Low Income: Bike: On average, for people in the low-income earning category (low-income households), the odds of using bike over other modes or 86.6% lower, all else being equal. This association is statistically significant at p< 0.05 (p= 0.0146995).

Low Income: Transit: On average, for householders in low-income households, the odds of using transit over other modes is 11.78% lower when compared to high income households, all else being equal. This association is not statistically significant.

Middle Income: Bike: On average, for people in middle-income households, the odds of using bike over other modes is 94.5% lower when compared to high income households, all else being equal. This association is statistically significant at p< 0.05 (p= 0.0000000036).

Middle Income: Transit: On average, for people in middle-income households, the odds of using transit over other modes is 46.35% lower when compared to high income households, all else being equal. This association is statistically significant at p< 0.05 (p= 0.0838109).

Upper Middle Income: Bike: On average, for people in upper middle-income households, the odds of using bike over other modes is 86.2% lower when compared to high income households, all else being equal. This association is statistically significant at p< 0.05 (p= 0.000055).

Upper Middle Income: Transit: On average, for people in upper middle-income households, the odds of using transit over other modes is 32.43% lower when compared to high income households, all else being equal. This association is not statistically significant.

“Based on our discussion above, on average, upper middle income householders and low income householders are similarly less likely to use bike over other modes, when compared to high income households, whereas, middle income householders are far less likely to use bike. On the other hand for transit, on average, middle and upper middle income householders are less likely to use transit over modes followed by low income householders, when compared to high income householders.”

  1. Type of neighborhood area’s or location’s impact on mode choice:

CBD: Bike: On average, for people living in the central business district, the odds of using bike over other modes is 43.23% lower when compared to people living in urban areas, all else being equal. This association is not statistically significant.

CBD: Transit: On average, for people living in the central business district, the odds of using transit over other modes is 105% higher when compared to people living in urban areas, all else being equal. This association is not statistically significant.

Model Prediction

An estimate of how good our model is to look at how well the predicts people’s mode choice. The following code predicts the probabilities of each mode (car, transit, bike) using the mod.1 model fitted earlier. It creates a data frame mode.prob containing these predicted probabilities. We calculated the actual share of each mode category in the observed data by dividing the frequency of each mode category in the mode_cat column by the total number of rows. We then assigned thresholds for each mode based on the share: 0.56 for car, 0.34 for transit and 0.08 for bike. A contingency table of the observed and predicted choice has been presented below.

#predicting
mode.prob <- data.frame(predict(mod.1, type = "response", newdata = dat.logit))
dat <- cbind.data.frame(dat, mode.prob)

dat$pred_mode <- 0

#use actual share in observed as thresholds
table(dat$mode_cat)/length(dat$mode_cat)
## 
##       bike        car    transit 
## 0.08946772 0.56625142 0.34428086
for (i in 1:length(dat$HH_ID)) {
  if (dat$car[i] > 0.56625142) {
    dat$pred_mode[i] = "car"
  } else if (dat$transit[i] > 0.34428086) {
    dat$pred_mode[i] = "transit"
  } else if (dat$bike[i] > 0.08946772) {
    dat$pred_mode[i] = "bike"
  }
}

table(predicted =dat$pred_mode, observed= dat$mode_cat)

We have also used the following metric to evaluate the goodness of fit of our model:

Count R squared: Count r2 is the total number of correct predictions over the total number of counts. It is a metric used to evaluate the goodness of fit of a model. In our case the Count R squared is 78.36% i.e. our model predicts 78.36% of the data correctly.

Misclassification error: It represents the proportion of incorrect predictions made by the model. It is calculated a (1- count r squared). It can also be expressed as the sum of false predictions divided by the total number of observations. Lower Misclassification Error indicates higher accuracy of the model in predicting the correct classes. In our case, the model incorrectly predicts 21.63% of mode choice in the data.


Adding Interventions:

We also wanted to see how well our model would predict if the existing conditions were changed. We made the following changes to our variables:

Cost: People in the Delaware valley region prefer car as a mode of transport. This is also due in part to the convenience and relative ease of purchasing a car in the US and cost of gas. We wanted to see if increasing the cost of driving the car by 50% would have an influence on its popularity. Concurrently, we wanted to check if reducing the cost of transit by 50% at the same time might improve ridership. Higher costs might lead to a decrease in car usage if other factors remain constant. It also aims to test if a reduction in transit costs leads to increased ridership, as lower costs can make transit more attractive compared to other modes of transport.

Time: To promote transit use even further, we also decided to reduce the time of traveling by transit by 20%. This intervention is intended to assess how a reduction in transit time influences people’s decisions regarding mode choice. Shorter travel times might make transit more appealing, potentially increasing its usage.

Extra Credit

DVRPC has hired you as a consultant to discuss what additional variable(s) you would recommend including in its next Household Travel Survey and why. These variables could be ones that reflect the changing transportation landscape since the last survey in 2012 and/or might have helped make your models predict better.

For this question, we have taken into consideration changes in travel pattern due to various policies, physical infrastructure and behavioral changes since 2012. There has been a shift in user trends since the pandemic. Work from home has become more commonplace which would affect the travel pattern for several households. In 2014, Uber was launched in Philadelphia and in 2017 Curb taxi mobile app was launched. These innovations have impacted the mode choice and opened by options. The above two examples have made a significant impact on transportation however these fall under categories “Worked at home for pay” and “Rideshare services”. Therefore they have not been included in the recommendations. We decided to include the following variables:

  1. Age: the current DVRPC household survey categorizes age variable. While categorical variable are suitable for looking at impact of travel choices on a group, Using age as a squared continuous variable instead allows us to model nonlinear relationships between age and the outcome variable within a single continuous scale. It can capture curved or U-shaped relationships where the effect of age changes non-linearly.

  2. HOV lane: high occupancy vehicle lane or Carpooling lane are special lanes that enable those who carpool or ride the bus to bypass the traffic in the adjacent, unrestricted (“general-purpose”) lanes. These lanes next to a highway or a toll road can reduce travel time. Nearly every State with HOV lanes reports that ridesharing and overall corridor person moving efficiency has increased since the lanes opened. Carpooling along with the use of EZ pass at no-cash tolls can potentially reduce travel delays. Adding it as a variable could help us examine its impact in the Delaware Valley region on time savings and mode choice.

  3. Congestion pricing: congestion pricing relies on dynamic pricing strategy designed to regulate demand by increasing prices without increasing supply. It can includes demand or surge pricing, segmented pricing, and peak-user pricing. As congestion pricing is implemented in New York city, we have assumed a case wherein this strategy is implemented in the Delaware Valley as a whole or in just the Philadelphia MSA. Cities like London and Stockholm that have implemented congestion pricing have experienced significant reductions in traffic congestion, improved air quality, and increased use of public transit and active modes. Such a strategy would surely impact the travel pattern and should have its own unique variable identifying if there was congestion pricing and how much did the user pay. This could help to look at what income group is willing to pay, who will shift to a different mode and what is the price threshold for different income groups. Predictions based using congestion pricing in a model with income, age, mode categories etc could surely help planners and engineers design for the future.

  4. Simulated congestion pricing: similarly to congestion pricing, it can be simulated based on actual numbers between daily recorded departure TAZ and arrival TAZ determined using a model; based on mode choice. The model could also potentially look at impact of congestion pricing on road safety for pedestrians and fatalities (https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35413616/). Simulation models based on congestion pricing scenarios can provide insights into potential travel behavior changes, revenue generation, and environmental benefits.

  5. Wait time: in our discussion above we used transit transfer and waiting time as a weighted measure of travel time. We had assumed a mean transfer time value however this information can also be collected directly from the riders as well. We want to look at wait time not just for public transit but also for rideshare services. We believe the wait time for rideshare may be greater in the suburbs or congested downtown which might affect people’s inclination to use it. Research on rideshare services has highlighted the importance of wait times in user satisfaction and mode choice. Thus we want to expand on the usage of the term as a variable in our future database. Collecting data on wait times for different transportation modes can help identify areas with longer wait times, assess user preferences, and improve service planning and operations to enhance the overall passenger experience.

  6. Simulated wait time: once we have a database on wait time across different counties and morphologies, We can design a simulation that mimics waiting for a bus over the course of one day or as needed. Simulated wait time scenarios can simulate real-world conditions and help evaluate the impact of infrastructure improvements or service enhancements on wait times. This approach can aid in optimizing transit operations, enhancing user experience, and encouraging modal shifts. Factors such as real-time information systems, transit frequency adjustments, and infrastructure enhancements can be tested through simulations to optimize wait times and promote modal shift as well.
